  {
    "source_type": "track_b",
    "software": "DWSIM",
    "topic": "CSTR Reactor Theory and Characteristics",
    "steps": [],
    "params": {},
    "ui_paths": [],
    "errors": [],
    "fixes": [],
    "theory": "Continuous Stirred Tank Reactors (CSTRs) are well-mixed reactors, typically used for homogeneous liquid-phase or gas-liquid reactions. Properties like temperature and density are constant throughout the reactor, and the outlet concentration equals the internal reactor concentration. CSTRs offer good temperature control but usually result in lower conversion and can have dead zones if mixing is imperfect. Levenspiel plots illustrate that CSTR volume for higher conversions can be significantly larger than PFRs due to exponential rate changes.",
    "source_url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O2n7XChXj_g",
    "license": "YouTube",
    "flag": "INCOMPLETE",
    "chunk_id": "60820918-1e1a-4734-9b1e-3e87557c3c3f"
  },
  {
    "source_type": "track_b",
    "software": "DWSIM",
    "topic": "CSTR Mole Balance Equation Derivation",
    "steps": [],
    "params": {
      "F_A0": "Molar flow rate entering reactor",
      "F_A": "Molar flow rate exiting reactor",
      "r_A": "Rate of reaction",
      "V": "Volume of reactor"
    },
    "ui_paths": [],
    "errors": [],
    "fixes": [],
    "theory": "The general mole balance equation is Input - Output + Generation = Accumulation. For a CSTR at steady state, accumulation is zero. Due to perfect mixing, the rate of reaction (r_A) is constant throughout the reactor, simplifying the generation term to r_A * V. This leads to an algebraic equation for the reactor volume: V = (F_A0 - F_A) / (-r_A).",
    "source_url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O2n7XChXj_g",
    "license": "YouTube",
    "flag": "INCOMPLETE",
    "chunk_id": "1f94802a-3368-48ce-a203-58476e459a02"
  },
